miRNAFAPp value

Requirement description

Divide the two indicators (miRNA and FAP protein) into four groups according to their levels, calculate the correlation and p-value between the two indicators, and display them using a heatmap.

http://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/78/7/1751

fromhttp://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/78/7/1751

Figure 4. EF, Comparison of the miR-508 ISH scores and the CALD1 and FAP IHC scores in colorectal cancer tissues. The correlations are shown in European cohort (n 128; E) and Renji cohort 2 (n 100; Fisher exact test; F).

Fishers exact test

miRNA

Application scenarios

Essentially, it is to classify continuous factors, study the correlation between two factors, display it using a contingency table heatmap, and conduct Fishers exact test.

Can be used to calculate and display the correlation between miRNA and target genes, or transcription factors and target genes.

Input file

easy_input.txt The observed values of two continuous variables in each sample. Each row contains one sample, and the two columns represent two observations, namely miRNA ISH scores and FAP IHC scores.

simdata <- read.table("easy_input.txt",header = T)

#  (Calculate the correlation coefficient between two continuous variables)

r.cor <- cor(simdata$miR.508, simdata$FAP)
#  (Print the correlation coefficient)
r.cor
## [1] -0.8
# p (Calculate the p-value for the correlation coefficient to test its significance)
#  (This result will also be used in the chart title)
p.cor <- cor.test(simdata$miR.508, simdata$FAP)$p.value
# p (Print the p-value)
p.cor
## [1] 1.8136e-23

###  ###
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13291308/generate-numbers-with-specific-correlation
simcor <- function (n, xmean, xsd, ymean, ysd, correlation) {
  x <- rnorm(n)
  y <- rnorm(n)
  z <- correlation * scale(x)[,1] + sqrt(1 - correlation^2) * 
    scale(resid(lm(y ~ x)))[,1]
  xresult <- xmean + xsd * scale(x)[,1]
  yresult <- ymean + ysd * z
  data.frame(x=xresult,y=yresult)
}

# 
r <- simcor(n = 100, xmean = 12, ymean = 30, xsd = 3, ysd = 4, correlation = -0.8) # 
simdata <- data.frame("miR.508" = r$x, "FAP" = r$y, stringsAsFactors = F, check.names = F)
write.table(simdata,"easy_input.txt",sep = "\t",row.names = F,quote = F)

Attachment: The input data here is simulated, and the generation method is as follows:

###Customize functions to simulate data###
#Reference for correlation simulation function https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13291308/generate-numbers-with-specific-correlation
simcor <- function (n, xmean, xsd, ymean, ysd, correlation) {
x <- rnorm(n)
y <- rnorm(n)
z <- correlation * scale(x)[,1] + sqrt(1 - correlation^2) * 
scale(resid(lm(y ~ x)))[,1]
xresult <- xmean + xsd * scale(x)[,1]
yresult <- ymean + ysd * z
data.frame(x=xresult,y=yresult)
}

#Simulated data
r <- simcor(n = 100, xmean = 12, ymean = 30, xsd = 3, ysd = 4, correlation = -0.8) #  Simulate negative correlation
simdata <- data.frame("miR.508" = r$x, "FAP" = r$y, stringsAsFactors = F, check.names = F)
write.table(simdata,"easy_input.txt",sep = "\t",row.names = F,quote = F)

PositiveModerateWeakNegative

Continuous variable classification

The example text divides both factors into four groups: positive, moderate, weak, and negative.

Therefore, we divide the data into four types based on quartiles:

# miR.508 (Classify data into four categories based on quartiles of miR.508 expression)
#  (Classification labels follow the example provided)
#  (Factor levels sorted in descending order for visualization)
simdata$miR.508_classify <- factor(cut(simdata$miR.508, quantile(simdata$miR.508), 
                                       labels = c("Negative", "Weak", "Moderate", "Positive")),
                                   levels = c("Positive", "Moderate", "Weak", "Negative")) 

#  (Alternative: classify data into two categories based on median)
#  (This line is commented out for reference)
#simdata$miR.508_classify <- factor(cut(simdata$miR.508, c(0, median(simdata$miR.508),max(simdata$miR.508)), 
#                                       labels = c("Negative", "Positive")), 
#                                   levels = c("Positive", "Negative"))

# FAP (Classify data into four categories based on quartiles of FAP expression)
#  (Classification labels consistent with the example)
#  (Factor levels sorted in ascending order)
simdata$FAP2_classify <- factor(cut(simdata$FAP, quantile(simdata$FAP), 
                             labels = c("Negative", "Weak", "Moderate", "Positive")), 
                         levels = c("Negative", "Weak", "Moderate", "Positive")) 

# miR.508FAP2 (Create contingency table for miR.508 and FAP2 classifications)
#  (Convert contingency table to data frame format)
tab_classify <- as.data.frame.array(table(simdata$miR.508_classify,simdata$FAP2_classify)) 
#  (Print contingency table to inspect results)
tab_classify
##          Negative Weak Moderate Positive
## Positive       18    5        1        0
## Moderate        3   13        6        3
## Weak            2    7       12        4
## Negative        1    0        6       17
# Fisher (Perform Fisher's exact test on the contingency table)
# workspace (Increase workspace for large contingency tables)
# 1e9 (Typical value of 1e9 suffices for most cases)
p.fisher <- fisher.test(tab_classify, workspace = 1e9)$p.value 
# Fisherp (Print p-value from Fisher's exact test)
p.fisher
## [1] 2.307314e-14

**Attention: * * Due to different sorting of strings or different horizontal and vertical coordinate numbers in the final contingency table, please carefully check the original data and count matrix after drawing to avoid mapping errors.

base plot

Start drawing

Below is a stroke by stroke plot using the base plot:

###  ###
#  (Define blue color palette for the plot)
blue   <- "#204F8D"  #  (Dark blue)
lblue  <- "#498EB9"  #  (Light blue)
dwhite <- "#B6D1E8"  #  (Very light blue)
white  <- "#E6EAF7"  #  (Near-white light blue)

# PDF5 (Create PDF output file with 5x5 inch dimensions)
pdf("ContigencyTable.pdf",width = 5,height = 5)

#  (Set plotting parameters)
par(bty="n", mgp = c(2,0.5,0), mar = c(5.1,6.1,4.1,2.1),tcl=-.25, font.main=3)
par(xpd=NA)  #  (Allow text to extend beyond plot area)

#  (Create a blank plot as the basis for the heatmap)
plot(c(0,ncol(tab_classify)),c(0,nrow(tab_classify)), #  (Set plot area range)
     col = "white", #  (Make points invisible)
     xlab = "",xaxt = "n", # x (Suppress x-axis)
     ylab = "",yaxt = "n") # y (Suppress y-axis)

# p (Set plot title with correlation and p-value information)
title(paste("Correlation between FAP and miR-508\nrho = ", round(r.cor,2), "; ", "P.cor = ", format(p.cor, digits = 3, scientific = T),
            "\nP.fisher = ", format(p.fisher, digits = 3, scientific = T)), adj = 0, line = 0)

#  (Draw y-axis)
axis(2, at = 0.5:(nrow(tab_classify)-0.5), labels = FALSE) # y (Generate y-axis tick marks)
text(y = 0.5:(nrow(tab_classify)-0.5), # y (Add y-axis labels)
     par("usr")[1], 
     labels = rownames(tab_classify)[nrow(tab_classify):1], #  (Reverse order to match example)
     srt = 0, pos = 2, xpd = TRUE)
mtext("Expression of miR-508", side=2, line = 4.5) # y (Add y-axis title)

#  (Draw x-axis)
axis(1, at = 0.5:(ncol(tab_classify)-0.5), labels = FALSE) # x (Generate x-axis tick marks)
text(x = 0.5:(ncol(tab_classify)-0.5), # x (Add x-axis labels)
     par("usr")[1] - 0.2, #  (Adjust label position)
     labels = colnames(tab_classify), 
     srt = 45, pos = 1, xpd = TRUE)
mtext("FAP", side=1, line = 3.5) # x (Add x-axis title)

#  (Generate linearly changing color palette)
input_matrix <- as.matrix(tab_classify) 
mat.max = max(input_matrix) #  (Maximum value in the matrix)
unq.value <- unique(sort(as.vector(input_matrix))) #  (Unique values in the matrix)
rbPal <- colorRampPalette(c(white,dwhite,lblue,blue)) #  (Create color gradient function)
col.vec <- rbPal(max(unq.value) + 1) # +1 (Generate colors for each unique value)
col.mat <- matrix(NA,byrow = T,ncol = ncol(input_matrix),nrow = nrow(input_matrix)) #  (Initialize color matrix)

#  (Fill color matrix based on count matrix)
for (i in 1:nrow(col.mat)) {
  for (j in 1:ncol(col.mat)) {
    col.mat[i,j] <- col.vec[input_matrix[i,j] + 1]
  }
}

#  (Create heatmap using rectangles)
x_size <- ncol(input_matrix)
y_size <- nrow(input_matrix)

my_xleft = rep(c(0:(x_size-1)),each = y_size) # x (Calculate left x-coordinates)
my_xright = my_xleft + 1 # x (Calculate right x-coordinates)
my_ybottom = rep(c((y_size-1):0),y_size) # y (Calculate bottom y-coordinates)
my_ytop = my_ybottom + 1 # y (Calculate top y-coordinates)
rect(xleft = my_xleft,
     ybottom = my_ybottom,
     xright = my_xright,
     ytop = my_ytop,
     col=col.mat, #  (Fill rectangles with colors)
     border = F) #  (Remove rectangle borders)

text(my_xleft + 0.5,my_ybottom + 0.5,input_matrix, cex = 1.3) #  (Add count values to rectangles)

invisible(dev.off()) #  (Close graphics device)
